48229	0	0.44090800145452724	0.041923214290461454	0.0903220935078167	-0.19558647763446574	-0.05929476930723924	-0.03736817752730792	-0.06407611164125927	0.07884404157836564	0.06407085063762728	-0.07113586423270181	-0.07981622167359996	-0.04485125131865131	-0.09928122106281287	0.006809286199033082	0.04759266384525103	-0.0031429562646726915	0.025481432861134263	0.028275838133335982	0.00175768333149851	0.04817250152361215	-0.0020573446979083383	0.04245522821996857	0.02185776781297994	0.032152941618206525	0.0010417693204096037	-0.014186186492773104	0.01909408763376268	0.01366671423941956	0.011617994853417007	-0.02140261850220219	0.013710288950375486	0.0021237305845262333	-0.016122975972521592	0.012466210175754087	0.00862630075932638	0.024345818089240766	0.02078035520633959	0.0005175689263692198	-0.02704835937845495	-0.051388791741765194	-0.007470223651992231	-0.011166285277766506	-0.019078158546955576	0.01157283157892655	-0.005455546750403544	-0.030889205557977816	-0.05493025623474323	-0.018825892922270913	0.0023828972345536084	-0.02856777907413249	The Truth In My Thoughts	depression really is an interesting thing.  you see people laugh at it,  but they don't really realize how deadly it is.  you see,  depression can come out of nothing.  there are at times that people are actually having fun with friends,  then all of the sudden they can't even smile.  you see,  depression is like seeing a baby,  anything being left by its mother.  you get this rush of dopamine in your brain,  because wow! look at that adorable baby! but when you look deeper down and take a closer look. . .  you see sadness.  and sometimes you live in it.  like a baby kangaroo in its mother's pouch.  some people get medication for their condition.  others can't afford it.  or don't know they even need it.  i'm the third one.  and the second one.  but i think i need to be the first one.  like my brother.  you see my life has been pretty tragic. . .  now some of you are rolling your eyes,  probably thinking,  ''oh yeah? try me.  i bet mines worse!'' well i don't know if mine is or not.  honestly,  if you look at my life from a strangers eyes,  you see a house.  a store,  clothes,  internet,  electricity,  a phone,  running water,  drinking water.  and so much more to be thankful for.  but if you look through my eyes or my friends and relatives,  you see a girl who lost her grandmother,  who was her best friend,  at the age of eleven.  a girl who almost lost her father at the age of twelve.  only to have him live,  but find there are harder days ahead.  with skin cancer,  which was removed,  but before that could happen he would stay in a coma for two weeks,  the hospital for so long his daughter lost count.  then finally,  get an emergency transplant to save his life,  and hopefully do some corrections to the poor life decisions he's made.  only to be later on bit in the but by another condition called diabetes,  to once again remind him of the decisions he's made.  a year later,  you would see the girls second oldest brother be diagnosed with a disease that makes the blood vessels in his hands constrict,  and this seems so little from what happened before,  but it just makes her think,  ''this may just be the beginning. '' oh,  how she wishes she were wrong,  only to be shown she's entirely right.  because a couple years later her oldest brother would be diagnosed with depression.  and she'll realize that the happiest people have the darkest minds.  she'll learn this again when her childhood best friend,  who moved away when she was going into 4th grade,  admits a history of self harm.  and once again when her other childhood best friend,  the one that made them the three musketeers,  admits to domestic violence in his home.  and again when her little cousin,  the one who grew up just a town away,  but seemed to always be only seconds away,  admits to having of thought of suicide. . .  and almost pulled it off,  thankfully that didn't happen thanks to the kid who had been hit by his father so many times he lost count.  but mostly she'll learn that she was right when she's six-teen.  and her mother will tell her that she was diagnosed with at least four types of cancer.  leading to days and nights of no sleep and no focus.  on particular night will always come to mind.  when she woke up to her mother getting sick.  she lays in bed thinking that her dad will hear and help,  because that's his job.  she'll sit there for a couple of minutes until her dad finally comes out.  she thinks,  ''finally,  i can get some rest. '' until her dad walks past her mom to go to the bathroom.  ''okay,  when he gets out he'll help. '' she thinks to herself.  until he comes out and goes back into his bedroom only after saying goodnight to his daughter.  then she'll work up the courage and go out there.  and as she helps her mother,  she'll read a text her mother sent to her father,  saying,  ''help'' you see,  that's when she loses it.  when she goes to school she wont be able to concentrate anymore.  she'll breakdown in front of her english teacher and basketball coaches first,  then her track coach,  and archery coach.  she'll finally tell her mother what's going on.  but when her mother offers to get her help,  she'll say,  ''i don't know. '' because she really doesn't.  she doesn't know if her family can afford it.  and she really doesn't know if she needs it.  but she does know,  deep down,  she should've said yes.  because she's cried more in these past seven months,  than she has in her whole life.  she'll find out the best way to get out her feelings is to write poetry.  but she wont ever let anyone read it.  it'll just sit in a book until she throws it away,  or until she moves it,  or someone finds it.  she'll secretly want someone to find it.  but she'll dread the day.  because even though she know she needs help,  she doesn't know how to ask for it.  or to accept it.  she doesn't know how to explain her feelings.  because when she was little and would cry all the time,  she was told to stop crying and man up.  she thought her feelings were not important.  she doesn't still think that.  instead she doesn't want to tell people because she's afraid they'll see her differently.  not the strong girl she wants to be.  but the weak broken one she is. 
